SIMPLE: preponderate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Preponderate
<hw>Pre*pon"der*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Preponderated</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Preponderating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>praeponderatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>praeponderare</ets>;
<ets>prae</ets> before + <ets>ponderare</ets> to weigh, fr.,
<ets>pondus</ets>, <ets>ponderis</ets>, a weight. See
<er>Ponder</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To outweigh; to overpower by
weight; to exceed in weight; to overbalance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An inconsiderable weight, by distance from the center of the
balance, will <qex>preponderate</qex> greater magnitudes.</q>
<rj><qau>Glanvill.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To overpower by stronger or moral power.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to prefer; to incline; to decide.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The desire to spare Christian blood <qex>preponderates</qex> him
for peace.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Preponderate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Preponderate
<hw>Pre*pon"der*ate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To exceed in weight;
hence, to incline or descend, as the scale of a balance; figuratively,
to exceed in influence, power, etc.; hence; to incline to one side;
<as>as, the affirmative side <ex>preponderated</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That is no just balance in which the heaviest side will not
<qex>preponderate</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Wilkins.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Preponderatingly</ent>⟦br⟧
